column1: #mapping_set_title: Mapping of MP terms to HPO terms from KidsFirst list

#mapping_set_description: "HPO terms were provided by the KidsFirst team from the set of terms used for patients in their cohorts. Initially the mapping date was not tracked so these were given the date of when we recieved the file (5/27/21). The set of HPO terms was updated on 5/17/212. Use of skos mappings terms: exact match: MP term is the same as the HPO term, ignoring that the HP term applies only to humans; broad match: MP term covers more than the HPO term; narrow match: MP term is more restircted than the HPO term, ignoring the species restriction; related match: MP term and HPO term share some similarity but would not have a parent-child relation in a shared ontology"

Issue is with the HPO definition that specifies the cause "resulting from inadequate passage of CSF from its point of production within the cerebral ventricles to its point of absorption", MP term does not specify a cause. However, both MP and HPO have non-obstructive hydrocephaly/Communicating hydrocephalus as a child term and this type of hydrocephaly does not have an issue with passage. The MP definition for the child term "abnormal cerebrospinal fluid absorption where there is no obstruction to fluid flow in the ventricular system" indicating that in this form the absorption is the issue. Based on child terms it is possibly that the hydrocephaly/hydrocephalus terms in MP and HP should be exact.

Spondylolisthesis is etymologically directionless and can be applied to both anterolisthesis and retrolisthesis. In clinical practice, spondylolisthesis is used synonymously with anterolisthesis. Often, particularly in the lower lumbar spine, it is due to spondylolysis (pars interarticularis defects). The MP term defintion includes both directions whereas the HPO term definition specifies anterior slippage due to complete bilateral fractures of the pars interarticularis.

The MP does not have a term for renal collecting system but looking at the HPO definition of duplicated collecting system, in particulatr "kidney with two (instead of, normally, one) pyelocaliceal systems.  The pyelocaliceal system is comprised of the renal pelvis and calices." and the Uberon and MP organization of renal pelvis and renal calyx (calyx is part of pelvis), it seemed to me that the MP double pelvis term is as close as I could get. There may be some distinction I'm missing as the HPO has a term for "Duplication of renal pelvis" (HP:0005580) but it is unclear to me how this is distinct from duplicated collecting system. I'm guessing that the pelvis includes parts that are not part of the collecting system? Uberon has a term for renal collecting system (UBERON:0004100) defined as collecting duct system of the kidney consists of a series of tubules and ducts that connect the nephrons to the ureter and this has no connection to the renal pelvis and calyx. Given that the duplicated HP term specifies pelvis and calices I would have expected some connection.

The MP term definition for chordee MP:0003555 specifies "acute angulation of the penis upon erection" and places chordee under abnormal penile erection MP:0001379, unlike HPO which places Chordee HP:0000041 under Abnormal penis morphology HP:0000036 and provides details on the direction of bowing and degree of angulation. I think the match is therefore "close" and the MP term should be placed under both abnormal penile erection and morphology (see https://educalingo.com/en/dic-en/chordee)
